{"title_page": "One size fits all", "text_new": "{{Other uses|One Size Fits All (disambiguation)}}\n{{Prose|date=September 2016}}\n\"'''One size fits all'''\" is a description for a product that would fit in all instances. The term has been extended to mean one style or procedure would fit in all related applications. It is an alternative for \"Not everyone fits the mold\n\".<ref name=\"EET\">\n  \"Tool targets faulty, 'one-size-fits-all' computer interfaces\",\n  July 2008, EETimes.com, web:\n  [http://www.eetimes.com/news/latest/<!--\n  -->showArticle.jhtml?articleID=209102259  EETimes-259].\n</ref><ref name=\"Wisc\">\n  \"[[Arsenic]] contamination lacks one-size-fits-all remedy\",\n  Jill Sakai, WISC.edu, December 10, 2007, web:\n  [http://www.news.wisc.edu/14545  WISC-14545].\n</ref>\nIt has been in use for over 5 decades. There are both positive and negative uses of the phrase.\n\n==History of the phrase==\nThe term ''\"one size fits all\"'' has been used as a common, cliche phrase for over 5 decades. It was already a popular term, in 1975, when [[Frank Zappa]] recorded the album ''[[One Size Fits All (Frank Zappa album)|One Size Fits All]]''.<ref name=\"lnk\">For source references, refer to each nearby linked article.</ref>\n\n==Positive views of the phrase==\nThere are several positive views of the phrase ''\"one size fits all\"'':\n\n:* A [[wristwatch]] could be considered as fitting all people.<ref name=lnk/>\n:* In women's clothing, a flexible or open garment can be labeled as one-size-fits-all; however, the size is typically a medium size (able to expand), rather than actually fitting petite or extra-large (XL) sizes.\n:* A neck chain could be designed to be worn by men or women.\n:* [[Bicycle helmet]]s with ring fit systems allow for a single size, also known as [[universal fit]].<ref name=lnk/><ref name=\"bhsi\">\n  \"One Size Fits All Bicycle Helmets\", BHSI, April 2009,\n  web: [http://www.bhsi.org/onesize.htm BHSI-onesiz].</ref>\n:* In military gear, some items have just one size (but smaller or larger people have already been excluded from military service).\n:* Many baseball hats available for commercial purchase are labeled \"one-size-fits-all\"\n\n==Negative views of the phrase==\nThere are many negative views of the phrase ''\"one size fits all\"'' including:\n:* Many customers prefer to have custom-tailored clothing.\n:* Men's [[Suit (clothing)|dress suit]]s typically have specific sizes for chest & waist measurements.<ref name=lnk/>\n:* [[Shoes]] are an example where sizes (and widths) vary depending on the specific person.<ref name=lnk/>\n:* For the [[United States|U.S.]] [[GI Bill]] in education, options and coverage will vary depending on each person.<ref name=lnk/>\n\nThis phrase has been shamed by men and women who find it offensive because no two people are alike. Everyone has a different body type and it isn\u2019t fair, for example, a plus sized woman who wants to buy an outfit that says one size fits all. It\u2019s excludes alternative body types from wearing the same clothes that \u201caverage\u201d body types can fit into.\n\nPolitically, the phrase has come to mean that methods of administration or political beliefs in one country should not necessarily be applied to another.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tailoring|Custom tailoring]]\n* [[Procrustes]]\n* [[Target marketing]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Slang]]\n[[Category:Clothing]]\n[[Category:Design]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|One Size Fits All (disambiguation)}}\n{{Prose|date=September 2016}}\n\"'''One size fits all'''\" is a description for a product that would fit in all instances. The term has been extended to mean one style or procedure would fit in all related applications. It is an alternative for \"Not everyone fits the mold\n\".<ref name=\"EET\">\n  \"Tool targets faulty, 'one-size-fits-all' computer interfaces\",\n  July 2008, EETimes.com, web:\n  [http://www.eetimes.com/news/latest/<!--\n  -->showArticle.jhtml?articleID=209102259  EETimes-259].\n</ref><ref name=\"Wisc\">\n  \"[[Arsenic]] contamination lacks one-size-fits-all remedy\",\n  Jill Sakai, WISC.edu, December 10, 2007, web:\n  [http://www.news.wisc.edu/14545  WISC-14545].\n</ref>\nIt has been in use for over 5 decades. There are both positive and negative uses of the phrase.\n\n==History of the phrase==\nThe term ''\"one size fits all\"'' has been used as a common, cliche phrase for over 5 decades. It was already a popular term, in 1975, when [[Frank Zappa]] recorded the album ''[[One Size Fits All (Frank Zappa album)|One Size Fits All]]''.<ref name=\"lnk\">For source references, refer to each nearby linked article.</ref>\n\n==Positive views of the phrase==\nThere are several positive views of the phrase ''\"one size fits all\"'':\n\n:* A [[wristwatch]] could be considered as fitting all people.<ref name=lnk/>\n:* In women's clothing, a flexible or open garment can be labeled as one-size-fits-all; however, the size is typically a medium size (able to expand), rather than actually fitting petite or extra-large (XL) sizes.\n:* A neck chain could be designed to be worn by men or women.\n:* [[Bicycle helmet]]s with ring fit systems allow for a single size, also known as [[universal fit]].<ref name=lnk/><ref name=\"bhsi\">\n  \"One Size Fits All Bicycle Helmets\", BHSI, April 2009,\n  web: [http://www.bhsi.org/onesize.htm BHSI-onesiz].</ref>\n:* In military gear, some items have just one size (but smaller or larger people have already been excluded from military service).\n:* Many baseball hats available for commercial purchase are labeled \"one-size-fits-all\"\n\n==Negative views of the phrase==\nThere are many negative views of the phrase ''\"one size fits all\"'' including:\n:* Many customers prefer to have custom-tailored clothing.\n:* Men's [[Suit (clothing)|dress suit]]s typically have specific sizes for chest & waist measurements.<ref name=lnk/>\n:* [[Shoes]] are an example where sizes (and widths) vary depending on the specific person.<ref name=lnk/>\n:* For the [[United States|U.S.]] [[GI Bill]] in education, options and coverage will vary depending on each person.<ref name=lnk/>\n\nPolitically, the phrase has come to mean that methods of administration or political beliefs in one country should not necessarily be applied to another.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tailoring|Custom tailoring]]\n* [[Procrustes]]\n* [[Target marketing]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Slang]]\n[[Category:Clothing]]\n[[Category:Design]]\n", "name_user": "2601:46:c803:2a10:8129:3c8:eed0:c506", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNegative views of the phrase:Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_size_fits_all"}
{"title_page": "Toyota Sports 800", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Toyota Sports 800 (UP15)\n| image = Toyota Sports 800 at History Garage.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Toyota]]\n| aka = <!-- \"Yotahachi (\u30e8\u30bf\u30cf\u30c1)\" is a nickname, not an alternative name -->\n| production = April 1965 \u2013 October 1969\n| assembly = Japan: [[Yokosuka]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture|Kanagawa]] ([[Kanto Auto Works]])\n| designer = Shozo Sato and [[Tatsuo Hasegawa]]\n| class = [[Sports car]]\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| related = [[Toyota Publica]]\n| engine = 790&nbsp;cc ''[[Toyota U engine#2U|2U-B]]'' [[Flat-twin engine|H2]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])\n| powerout = {{convert|33|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}}\n| transmission = 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2000|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|3580|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1465|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1175|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|580|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| sp = uk\n}}\n\nThe {{nihongo|'''Toyota Sports 800'''|Japanese: \u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30fb\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4800|Toyota Sup\u014dtsu Happiyaku}} is [[Toyota]]'s first production [[sports car]]. The prototype for the Sports 800, called the [[Toyota Publica Sports|Publica Sports]], debuted at the 1962 [[Tokyo Auto Show]], featuring a space age sliding canopy and utilizing the {{convert|21|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}} powertrain of the [[Toyota Publica|Publica]] 700, a Japanese market economy car. The Toyota Sports 800 is affectionately called the \"Yota-Hachi\" (\u30e8\u30bf\u30cf\u30c1), which is a Japanese short form for \"Toyota 8\". In Japan, the vehicle was exclusive to Toyota Japan retail sales channel called ''[[Toyota#Japan|Toyota Publica Store]]'' alongside the Publica.\n\n== History ==\nThe car went into production in 1965,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ne.jp/asahi/ts800/hp/ENGLISH/index.html |title=TOYOTA SPORTS 800's page |publisher=Ne.jp |date= |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref> with chassis code UP15 and an increase in [[Toyota U engine|engine]] displacement from 700 cc to 800 cc, as well as dual carburetors, which increased power from {{convert|28|to|45|PS|abbr=on}}. This engine was sufficient to power the light car around town at {{convert|45|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on|disp=flip|-1}} or on a race track up to about {{convert|160|km/h|mph|-1|abbr=on}}. Production started after the introduction of Honda's first car, called the [[Honda S500]], and joined the market segment that was already represented by the [[Datsun Fairlady]], and the [[Daihatsu Compagno]].\n\nThe car had aerodynamic styling by Shozo Sato, a designer on loan from Datsun, and Toyota engineer [[Tatsuo Hasegawa]]. Hasegawa had been an aircraft designer in World War II and the resulting Sports 800 was a lightweight and agile machine.<ref>http://members.aol.com/pinealguy/tatsuo.htm</ref> The Sports 800 was one of the first production cars featuring a lift-out roof panel, or [[targa top]], pre-dating the Porsche Targa. The aluminum [[targa top]] could be stored in the trunk, when not in use.\n\nBetween 1965 and 1969 approximately 3,131 units were built by Toyota subcontractor [[Kanto Auto Works]]. Only about 10% of those vehicles are known to have survived, most being in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kanto-aw.co.jp/en/corporate/history/|title=\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u81ea\u52d5\u8eca\u6771\u65e5\u672c\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|publisher=Kanto-aw.co.jp|accessdate=2012-10-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508094505/http://www.kanto-aw.co.jp/en/corporate/history/|archivedate=2012-05-08}}</ref>\n\nProduction Tables{{Where|date=July 2011}} show 1,235 cars manufactured in 1965, 703 in 1966, 538 in 1967, 440 in 1968, and 215 in 1969.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\n[[File:1967 Toyota Sports 800.jpg|thumb|A 1967 Toyota Sports 800 in [[left-hand drive]] configuration]]\n[[File:1965 Toyota Sports-800 02.jpg|thumb|Rear view of 1965 Sports 800 with roof panel removed]]\n\nThe vast majority of the 3,131 cars were right hand drive, but some 300 were [[left hand drive]] models, built primarily for the [[Okinawa]] market. (Okinawa, having been American occupied, drove on the \"other side\" from the rest of Japan.) A very limited number of left hand drive cars were used by Toyota to \"test drive\" in the US, but Toyota made a decision not to import or sell the cars in the US market.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\nThere are subtle design differences between the years. Noticeable differences have included: change over from non-synchro to [[Syncromesh|synchro]] first gear in 1967; a grill and bumperette change in 1968; and side marker lights in 1969. The basic body design, however, remained unchanged.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\nAn air-cooled 790&nbsp;cc horizontally opposed two-cylinder [[Flat-twin|boxer]] engine powered the vehicle. The 0.8 liter [[Toyota U engine|2U]] (45&nbsp;PS at 5,400&nbsp;rpm) was produced from 1965 through 1969, while a similar [[Toyota U engine|2U-B]] was produced from 1966 through 1976 (in 1975 the [[Toyota Dyna|Dyna Coaster Bus]] manual shows that Toyota used the [[Toyota U engine|2U-B]] as a separate auxiliary engine, just to run the air conditioning unit for the bus). In a less tuned form, the [[Toyota U engine|2U]] was also used in the Publica (UP20/UP26) and [[Toyota MiniAce|MiniAce]] (UP100).<ref>{{citation | script-title=ja:\u611b\u3055\u308c\u308b\u8eca\u3065\u304f\u308a\u3002\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u306f\u3042\u3059\u306b\u3044\u3069\u307f\u307e\u3059\u3002|trans-title=Lovable car manufacture. Toyota dares to defy tomorrow. | language = Japanese | year = 1972 | type = catalog | publisher = Toyota Motor Co. | pages = 3\u20134 }}</ref>\n\nWeight was kept down by using aluminum on selected body panels and thin steel on the unibody construction. For the first few years of production even the seat frames were made of aluminum.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\nThere are both Japanese and American Registries on the Internet. Owners are encouraged to register their vehicles.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\n[[File:Toyota-Sports800EV.jpg|thumb|Toyota Sports 800 EV Twin]]\n\nToyota produced a one-off prototype [[Toyota Sports 800 Gas Turbine Hybrid|Sports 800 Gas Turbine Hybrid]] for the 1979 [[Tokyo Motor Show]].<ref name=\"showcars\">{{cite book | title=Japanese Showcars 2 Tokyo Motor Show 1970~1979| year=2008| location=Japan| isbn=978-4-544-91033-9}}</ref> The body of the Sports 800 also served as basis of the [[Toyota Sports EV|Sports EV]] and [[Toyota Sports EV Twin|Sports EV Twin]] electric concept cars, both unveiled in 2010.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Toyota Publica Sports]]\n* [[Toyota Publica]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Toyota 2000GT Sports 800, Neko Publishing Co., Ltd.\n* Toyota Publica & Sports 800, Miki Press.\n* Toyota Sports 800 Production Figure Documents from Toyota Motor Corporation, Global External Affairs Division.\n* 1968 Toyota Motor Sales, USA Press Release.\n* 1975 Toyota Dyna Coaster Bus Manual.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Toyota Sports 800}}\n* [http://www.rstreet.us/yotahachi/toyota_700_800_online_reg.htm North American Owner's Registry].\n* [http://www.ne.jp/asahi/ts800/hp/MAIN/list.html Japanese Owner's Registry].\n* [http://autos.groups.yahoo.com/group/Toy700and800/ Yahoo Groups Toyota 700 and 800 Publica and Sports 800 Group].\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071213025206/http://tsocyota8.hp.infoseek.co.jp/ Japanese Club Page].\n* [http://www.rstreet.us/yotahachi/ Yotahachi North American Resource Page].\n* [http://www.bcchapel.org/pages/0003/S800/Index.html Original S800/UP15 Sales Brochure].\n{{Toyota cars}}\n{{Toyota road cars timeline, 1955-1984}}\n\n[[Category:Toyota vehicles|Sports 800]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Roadsters]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by boxer engines]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1965]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Toyota Sports 800 (UP15)\n| image = Toyota Sports 800 at History Garage.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Toyota]]\n| aka = <!-- \"Yotahachi (\u30e8\u30bf\u30cf\u30c1)\" is a nickname, not an alternative name -->\n| production = April 1965 \u2013 October 1969\n| assembly = Japan: [[Yokosuka]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture|Kanagawa]] ([[Kanto Auto Works]])\n| designer = Shozo Sato and [[Tatsuo Hasegawa]]\n| class = [[Sports car]]\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| related = [[Toyota Publica]]\n| engine = 790&nbsp;cc ''[[Toyota U engine#2U|2U-B]]'' [[Flat-twin engine|H2]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])\n| powerout = {{convert|33|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}}\n| transmission = 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2000|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|3580|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1465|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1175|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|580|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| sp = uk\n}}\n\nThe {{nihongo|'''Toyota Sports 800'''|Japanese: \u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30fb\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4800|Toyota Sup\u014dtsu Happiyaku}} is [[Toyota]]'s first production [[sports car]]. The prototype for the Sports 800, called the [[Toyota Publica Sports|Publica Sports]], debuted at the 1962 [[Tokyo Auto Show]], featuring a space age sliding canopy and utilizing the {{convert|21|kW|hp PS|abbr=on|0}} powertrain of the [[Toyota Publica|Publica]] 700, a Japanese market economy car. The Toyota Sports 800 is affectionately called the \"Yota-Hachi\" (\u30e8\u30bf\u30cf\u30c1), which is a Japanese short form for \"Toyota 8\". In Japan, the vehicle was exclusive to Toyota Japan retail sales channel called ''[[Toyota#Japan|Toyota Publica Store]]'' alongside the Publica.\n\n== History ==\nThe car went into production in 1965,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ne.jp/asahi/ts800/hp/ENGLISH/index.html |title=TOYOTA SPORTS 800's page |publisher=Ne.jp |date= |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref> with chassis code UP15 and an increase in [[Toyota U engine|engine]] displacement from 700 cc to 800 cc, as well as dual carburetors, which increased power from {{convert|28|to|45|PS|abbr=on}}. This engine was sufficient to power the light car around town at {{convert|45|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on|disp=flip|-1}} or on a race track up to about {{convert|160|km/h|mph|-1|abbr=on}}. Production started after the introduction of Honda's first car, called the [[Honda S500]], and joined the market segment that was already represented by the [[Datsun Fairlady]], and the [[Daihatsu Compagno]].\n\nThe car had aerodynamic styling by Shozo Sato, a designer on loan from Datsun, and Toyota engineer [[Tatsuo Hasegawa]]. Hasegawa had been an aircraft designer in World War II and the resulting Sports 800 was a lightweight and agile machine.<ref>http://members.aol.com/pinealguy/tatsuo.htm</ref> The Sports 800 was one of the first production cars featuring a lift-out roof panel, or [[targa top]], pre-dating the Porsche Targa. The aluminum [[targa top]] could be stored in the trunk, when not in use.\n\nBetween 1965 and 1969 approximately 3,131 units were built by Toyota subcontractor [[Kanto Auto Works]]. Only about 10% of those vehicles are known to have survived, most being in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kanto-aw.co.jp/en/corporate/history/|title=\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u81ea\u52d5\u8eca\u6771\u65e5\u672c\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|publisher=Kanto-aw.co.jp|accessdate=2012-10-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508094505/http://www.kanto-aw.co.jp/en/corporate/history/|archivedate=2012-05-08}}</ref>\n\nProduction Tables{{Where|date=July 2011}} show 1,235 cars manufactured in 1965, 703 in 1966, 538 in 1967, 440 in 1968, and 215 in 1969.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\n[[File:1967 Toyota Sports 800.j