{"title_page": "List of American heiresses", "text_new": "[[File:Princess Murat.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Catherine Willis Gray]], who became Princess Murat]]\n[[Image:Frances Work 2163454306 8fa8ee30e6 o.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Frances Ellen Work|Frances Work]], great-grandmother of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]]]]\n[[File:Consuelo Yznaga.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Consuelo Montagu, Duchess of Manchester]], by [[John Singer Sargent]], 1907]]\n[[File:Mary Leiter, Lady Curzon, wearing a 1903 gown by Jean-Philippe Worth - William Logsdail 1909 portrait.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Mary Curzon, Baroness Curzon of Kedleston|Mary Curzon]], Marchioness Curzon of Kedleston, [[Governor-General of India#Style and title|Vicereine of India]].]]\n[[File:Consuelo Balson LCCN2003663444.tif|thumb|200px|[[Consuelo Vanderbilt]], a member of the [[Vanderbilt family]] who became Duchess of Marlborough]]\n[[File:Nancy Astor.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Nancy Astor, Viscountess Astor]].]] \n[[File:Countess Granard.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Beatrice Forbes, Countess of Granard]].]]\n[[File:GENETierney (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Gene Tierney#Personal life|Countess Oleg Cassini Loiewski]]]]\n[[File:Lady Hartington.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Kathleen Cavendish, Marchioness of Hartington]] (n\u00e9e Kathleen Kennedy).]]\n[[File:Grace Kelly MGM photo.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Grace Kelly|Grace Kelly, the Princess of Monaco]].]]\n\nThis is a list of some American [[socialite]]s, from before the [[Gilded Age]] to the end of the 20th century, who married into the European nobility, peerage or royalty. The titles in this list are all mentioned or translated into English.\n\n==Before 1865==\n* [[Vincent Rumpff|Countess Vincent von Rumpff]] (''[[Given name#Name at birth|n\u00e9e]]'' Eliza [[John Jacob Astor|Astor]]) on 25 October 1825.<ref name=\"Derbyshire2009\">{{cite book |last1=Derbyshire |first1=Wyn |title=Six Tycoons: The Lives of John Jacob Astor, Cornelius Vanderbilt, Andrew Carnegie, John D. Rockefeller, Henry Ford and Joseph P. Kennedy |date=2009 |publisher=Spiramus Press Ltd |isbn=978-1-904905-85-1 |page=24 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R8A8XeUWt_EC&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Marianne Wellesley, Marchioness Wellesley]] (''n\u00e9e'' Marianne [[Charles Carroll of Carrollton#Family|Caton]], previously Patterson) on 29 October 1825<ref name=\"Cokayne\">G.E. Cokayne; with Vicary Gibbs, H.A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, Duncan Warrand and Lord Howard de Walden, editors, The Complete Peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant, Extinct or Dormant, new ed., 13 volumes in 14 (1910-1959; reprint in 6 volumes, Gloucester, U.K.: Alan Sutton Publishing, 2000), volume IX, page 238. </ref>\n* [[Catherine Willis Gray|Catherine Murat, Princess Murat and Princess of Naples]] (''n\u00e9e'' Catherine Daingerfield Willis, previously Gray) on 12 July 1826<ref name=\"Davis2011\">{{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=Betty |last2=Trackers |first2=Big Bend Ghost |title=Haunted Monticello, Florida |date=2011 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |isbn=978-1-62584-155-1 |page=8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NrZ_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT78 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Lucien, 3rd Prince Murat|Caroline Murat, Princess Murat]] (''n\u00e9e'' Caroline Georgina Fraser) on 18 August 1831<ref name=\"PrinceMuratObit1878\">{{cite news |title=Obituary.; Prince Murat. |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1878/04/12/80680225.html?pageNumber=4 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 April 1878 |page=4}}</ref>\n* [[Charles, marquis de La Valette|Adeline de La Valette, Marquise de La Valette]] (''n\u00e9e'' Adeline Fowle, previously Welles) in 1842<ref name=\"vam\">{{cite web |title=Bust of la Marquise de la Valette {{!}} Carpeaux, Jean-Baptiste |url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O117013/bust-of-la-marquise-de-bust-carpeaux-jean-baptiste/ |website=collections.vam.ac.uk |publisher=[[Victoria and Albert Museum]] |accessdate=13 March 2020 |language=en |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Mary Cunard, Lady [[Cunard baronets|Cunard]]  (''n\u00e9e'' Mary Bache [[Bache McEvers#Personal life|McEvers]]) in May 1849<ref name=\"Burke's1914\">{{cite book |title=Burke's Genealogical and Heraldic History of Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage |date=1914 |publisher=Burke's Peerage Limited |page=547 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RVggAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA547 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Mary von Waldersee|Princess Frederick of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Augustenburg]], Princess von Noer on 3 November 1864, then Countess [[Alfred von Waldersee]] on 14 April 1874 (''n\u00e9e'' Mary Esther Lee)<ref name=\"1914Obit\">{{cite news |last1=TIMES |first1=Special Cable to THE NEW YORK |title=COUNTESS VON WALDERSEE.; Widow of Famous Field Marshal Was Daughter of a New York Merchant. |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1914/07/06/101920466.html?pageNumber=7 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=6 July 1914 |page=7}}</ref>\n\n==From 1865 to 1965==\nAfter the beginning of the [[Reconstruction Era]] and the [[Gilded Age]] (at the end of the [[American Civil War]] on 9 May 1865):\n\n*[[The Honourable#United Kingdom|The Hon.]] Mrs Ralph [[Edward Harbord, 3rd Baron Suffield|Harbord]] (''n\u00e9e'' Elizabeth Pole [[Mary Schenley|Schenley]]) on 5 September 1865<ref name=\"Fleming1922\">{{cite book |last1=Fleming |first1=George Thornton |title=History of Pittsburgh and Environs: From Prehistoric Days to the Beginning of the American Revolution ... |date=1922 |publisher=American historical society, Incorporated |page=101 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5so0AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA101&lpg=PA101 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Thomas E. Davis#Family|Mathilde Lante Montefeltro della Rovere]], Princess and Duchess Lante Montefeltro della Rovere (''n\u00e9e'' Mathilde ''\"Tilly\"'' Davis) on 28 April 1866<ref>{{cite web|title=The Heirs of Europe LANTE DELLA ROVERE|url=http://heirsofeurope.blogspot.co.uk/2010/01/lante-montefeltro-della-rovere.html|work=see line 32 & 33|publisher=Ronald Elward 2009-2014|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> \n*[[Elizabeth Beers-Curtis|Elizabeth de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]], Marquise de Talleyrand (''n\u00e9e'' Elizabeth Beers-Curtis) on 18 March 1867<ref>{{cite news |title=Miscellaneous Items |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/50377761 |accessdate=10 February 2019 |work=[[The Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] |date=April 27, 1867 |page=4 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Elise, Countess of Edla]] (''n\u00e9e'' Elise ''\"Elisa\"'' Friedericke Hensler) on 10 June 1869<ref>{{cite news |last1=TIMES |first1=Special Cable to THE NEW YORK |title=COUNTESS EDLA, 93, NOTED SINGER, DIES; Boston Girl's Voice Won Dom Fernando, Portugal's ExKing, for a Husband.A PRIMA DONNA IN 1860Singer, as Elsie Hensler, ScoredTriumphs Here--Her Father aGerman Political Refugee. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/05/22/archives/countess-edla-93-noted-singer-dies-boston-girls-voice-won-dom.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=22 May 1929}}</ref>\n*[[Lady Randolph Churchill|Lady Randolph Spencer-Churchill]] (''n\u00e9e'' Jeanette ''\"Jennie\"'' Jerome, aka {{underline|the first known ''American Dollar Princess''}} in Europe) on 15 April 1874<ref>{{cite news |title=Lady Randolph Churchill. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/06/30/archives/lady-randolph-churchill.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=30 June 1921}}</ref>\n*[[Alice Heine|Alice Chapelle de Jumilhac]], Duchess de Richelieu on 27 February 1875, then Princess of Monaco on 30 October 1889 (''n\u00e9e'' Alice Heine)<ref>{{cite news |title=EX-PRINCESS OF MONACO.; Former Alice Heine of New Orleans Dies Suddenly in Paris, |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/12/23/archives/exprincess-of-monaco-former-alice-heine-of-new-orleans-dies.html?sear