airall", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFrom 1865 to 1965:added a reference and made a revision based on that", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_American_heiresses"}
{"title_page": "Angelo Di Livio", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2008}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Angelo Di Livio\n| image              = KL 2018 (3).jpg\n| caption            = Di Livio in [[Italy national football team|Italy]] colours, 2018\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1966|7|26}}\n| birth_place        = Rome, Italy\n| height             = 1.73 m\n| position           = [[Midfielder]], [[Defender (association football)|defender]]\n| years1             = 1984\u20131985 |clubs1 = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]              |caps1 = 0   |goals1 = 0\n| years2             = 1985\u20131986 |clubs2 = [[A.C. Reggiana|Reggiana]]      |caps2 = 13  |goals2 = 0\n| years3             = 1986\u20131987 |clubs3 = [[A.G. Nocerina 1910|Nocerina]] |caps3 = 31  |goals3 = 1\n| years4             = 1987\u20131989 |clubs4 = [[A.C. Perugia|Perugia]]        |caps4 = 72  |goals4 = 4\n| years5             = 1989\u20131993 |clubs5 = [[Padova Calcio|Padova]]        |caps5 = 138 |goals5 = 13\n| years6             = 1993\u20131999 |clubs6 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]      |caps6 = 186 |goals6 = 3\n| years7             = 1999\u20132005 |clubs7 = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]   |caps7 = 169 |goals7 = 8\n| totalcaps          = 609 |totalgoals = 29\n| nationalyears1     = 1995\u20132002 |nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] |nationalcaps1 = 40 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{ITA}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Association football}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Football Championship]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[UEFA Euro 2000|Belgium-Netherlands 2000]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Angelo Di Livio''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8and\u0292elo di \u02c8li\u02d0vjo}}; born 26 July 1966) is an Italian former professional [[Association football|football]] [[midfielder]] and [[Defender (association football)|defender]]. He played for several Italian clubs in [[Serie A]] throughout his career, coming to prominence with [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], where he won several domestic and international titles. At international level he also played for the [[Italy national football team|Italian national side]] in two [[FIFA World Cup]]s and two [[UEFA European Football Championship]]s, reaching the final of [[UEFA Euro 2000]].\n\nDuring his playing career he was known as ''soldatino'' (toy soldier) or ''soldatino Di Livio'', a nickname his Juventus teammate at the time [[Roberto Baggio]] gave him because of Di Livio's characteristic way of running up and down the flank.<ref name=\"soldatino\">{{cite news|url=http://www.pianeta-calcio.it/?page=vedi_incontri_vip&id=257|title=Io, \"Soldatino\" Di Livio|date= 23 September 2011 |accessdate= 10 March 2013 |work = Pianeta-Calcio.it }}</ref><ref name=\"cinquantamila\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cinquantamila.it/storyTellerThread.php?threadId=DI+LIVIO+Angelo|title=Biografia di Angelo Di Livio|publisher=www.cinquantamila.it|language=Italian|author1=Maria Elena Ribezzo|author2=Giorgio Dell'Arti|date=17 January 2014|accessdate=29 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in Rome, Di Livio began his career with [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] in 1984. Having failed to make an appearance in his only season for the club, Di Livio played for [[A.C. Reggiana|Reggiana]] (1985\u201386), [[A.G. Nocerina 1910|Nocerina]] (1986\u201387), [[A.C. Perugia|Perugia]] (1987\u201389), [[Padova Calcio|Padova]] (1989\u201393), [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] (1993\u201399) and [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] (1999\u20132005).\n\nHis tireless running and quality crossing made him an important element in the dominant Juventus starting lineup from 1993 to 1999, during one of the most successful periods in the club's history. With Juventus, he won three ''[[Scudetto|scudetti]]'' (Italian A League; [[1994\u201395 Serie A|1995]], [[1996\u201397 Serie A|1997]], [[1997\u201398 Serie A|1998]]) and one [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] title ([[1996 UEFA Champions League Final|1996]]), in addition to two [[Italian Supercup]]s ([[1995 Supercoppa Italiana|1995]], [[1997 Supercoppa Italiana|1997]]), a [[1994\u201395 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], an [[UEFA Supercup]] ([[1996 UEFA Super Cup|1996]]), and an [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]] ([[1996 Intercontinental Cup|1996]]); he also reached the final of the [[1994\u201395 UEFA Cup]].\n\nIn 1999, he moved to Fiorentina, where he [[Captain (association football)|captained]] the team to win the [[2000\u201301 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] during the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301 season]]. In 2002, when AC Fiorentina went bankrupt and was reborn as ''Florentia Viola'' in [[Serie C2]], Di Livio showed his dedication by being the only player to stay with the team, as he played through the depths of Italian football on the climb back to [[Serie A]] in 2004, finally retiring after the conclusion of the [[2004\u201305 Serie A]] season.\n\n==International career==\nDi Livio was capped 40 times for [[Italy national football team|Italy]]. He played for Italy at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]], the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], [[2000 UEFA European Football Championship|Euro 2000]] (where Italy finished in 2nd place), and the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]. His first cap came on 6 September 1995 against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]]; his last on 18 June 2002 against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]]. At Euro 1996, he set-up [[Pierluigi Casiraghi]]'s first goal in the team's 2\u20131 win in the opening group match against [[Russia national football team|Russia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52507/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Instinctive Casiraghi helps Italy sink Russia|publisher=UEFA.com|date=6 October 2003}}</ref> For Italy, he was often used as a holding player to shut down games when the team was ahead, thus sealing the win.\n\n==After retirement==\nAfter retiring, Di Livio worked as a coach in the A.S. Roma Youth System (''Allievi \"Coppa Lazio\"'').<ref>[http://www.asroma.it/GiovaniliList.aspx?Categoria=18 Official AS Roma's site]</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nA quick, experienced, energetic, combative, reliable, and tactically versatile player, Di Livio was usually deployed on the right wing, although he was capable of playing on either flank, as a [[Midfielder#Winger|wide midfielder]], or as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|full-back]] or [[Defender (association football)#Wing-back|wing-back]]; he was also capable of playing in the [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|centre]], as a [[Midfielder#Box-to-box midfielder|box-to-box]] or [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], or even in [[Defender (association football)|defence]]. Although he was not the most naturally talented or skilled footballer, he was a highly consistent player, who was known for his pace, stamina, work-rate, strength, tenacity, mentality, man-marking ability, and [[Cross (football)|crossing]] accuracy, as well as his ability to make attacking runs down the flank, but also track back, which enabled him to cover the wing effectively, and have a successful career.<ref name=\"soldatino\"/><ref name=\"cinquantamila\"/><ref name=\"euro2000\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/italy/squad/774613.stm|title=Euro 2000 Profile: Angelo Di Livio|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"tuttomercatoweb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/rassegna-stampa/di-livio-capello-non-mi-volle-alla-roma-41347|title=Di Livio: \"Capello non mi volle alla Roma\"|publisher=TuttoMercatoWeb.com|language=Italian|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"tuttojuve\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-angelo-di-livio-26504|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Angelo DI LIVIO|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|author=Stefano Bedeschi|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"glance\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/1022803.stm|title=Italy squad at a glance|publisher=BBC|accessdate=7 November 2015|date=14 November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/euro2000/italy/player/delivio.html|title=Profile: Angelo Di Livio|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Phil Cole|date=13 July 2000|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it//1998/luglio/03/Niente_paura_noi_siamo_Italia_ga_0_9807033059.shtml |title=\" Niente paura, noi siamo l' Italia \" |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |author1=Germano Bovolenta |author2=Nicola Cecere |date=3 July 1998 |accessdate=13 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAngelo's son, [[Lorenzo Di Livio|Lorenzo]], is also a footballer;<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.italianfootballdaily.com/serie-keeping-la-famiglia/|title=Serie A- Keeping in it in La Famiglia {{!}} IFD|last=Mason|first=Joshua|date=12 September 2016|work=www.italianfootballdaily.com|publisher=Italian Football Daily|language=en-US|access-date=25 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126005507/http://www.italianfootballdaily.com/serie-keeping-la-famiglia/|archivedate=26 November 2016}}</ref> a Roma youth product, he currently plays for [[Urbs Sportiva Reggina 1914|Reggina]], on loan from Roma.\n\n==Endorsements==\nAs one of the most popular footballers from his generation, Di Livio has kept his public influence and positive reputation till today. In 2011, Angelo Di Livio was named as \"Brand ambassador\" for [[SKS365]]'s brand planetwin365.<ref name=\"http://sks365.com/planetwin365-renews-cooperation-with-angelo-di-livio/\">planetwin365 renews cooperation with Angelo Di Livio: [http://sks365.com/planetwin365-renews-cooperation-with-angelo-di-livio/ sks365 - planetwin365 renews cooperation with Angelo Di Livio], accessdate: 26 August 2015</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref>{{NFT|10693|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[Coppa Italia]]\n!colspan=2|[[UEFA|Europe]]\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[A.S. Roma|Roma]]||1984\u201385||[[Serie A]]||0||0||||||||||||\n|-\n|[[A.C. Reggiana 1919|Reggiana]]||1985\u201386||[[Lega Pro Prima Divisione|Serie C1]]||13||0||||||||||||\n|-\n|[[A.S.G. Nocerina|Nocerina]]||1986\u201387||Serie C1||31||1||||||||||||\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[A.C. Perugia Calcio|Perugia]]||1987\u201388||[[Lega Pro Seconda Divisione|Serie C2]]||34||3||||||||||||\n|-\n|1988\u201389||rowspan=2|Serie C1||33||1||||||||||||\n|-\n|1989\u201390||5||0||||||||||||\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Calcio Padova|Padova]]||1989\u201390||rowspan=4|[[Serie B]]||29||2||||||||||||\n|-\n|1990\u201391||36||3||||||||||||\n|-\n|1991\u201392||36||3||||||||||||\n|-\n|1992\u201393||36||3||||||||||||\n|-\n|rowspan=6|[[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]||1993\u201394||rowspan=6|Serie A||33||0||||||||||||\n|-\n|1994\u201395||27||1||||||||||||\n|-\n|1995\u201396||32||2||||||||||||\n|-\n|1996\u201397||32||1||||||||||||\n|-\n|1997\u201398||30||0||||||||||||\n|-\n|1998\u201399||33||1||||||||||||\n|-\n|rowspan=6|[[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]||1999\u201300||rowspan=3|Serie A||30||1||||||||||||\n|-\n|2000\u201301||33||1||||||||||||\n|-\n|2001\u201302||32||1||||||||||||\n|-\n|2002\u201303||[[Lega Pro Seconda Divisione|Serie C2]]||21||0||||||||||||\n|-\n|2003\u201304||[[Serie B]]||43||4||||||||||||\n|-\n|2004\u201305||Serie A||12||0||||||||||||\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n!611||28||||||||||||\n|}\n\n===International===\n[[File:Ned-AllStars (3).jpg|thumb|upright|Di Livio in 2014]]\n:Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/dilivio-intl.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=13 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527222400/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/dilivio-intl.html|archivedate=27 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Italy national football team|Italy national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1995||2||0\n|-\n|1996||7||0\n|-\n|1997||10||0\n|-\n|1998||6||0\n|-\n|1999||2||0\n|-\n|2000||5||0\n|-\n|2001||5||0\n|-\n|2002||3||0\n|-\n!Total||40||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Juventus'''<ref name=eurosport.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/angelo-di-livio_prs322/person.shtml|title=Angelo Di Livio|publisher=Eurosport|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1994\u201395 Serie A|1994\u201395]], [[1996\u201397 Serie A|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Serie A|1997\u201398]]\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1994\u201395 Coppa Italia|1994\u201395]]\n*[[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[1995 Supercoppa Italiana|1995]], [[1997 Supercoppa Italiana|1997]]\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[1995\u201396 UEFA Champions League|1995\u201396]]\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[1996 UEFA Super Cup|1996]]\n*[[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]: [[1996 Intercontinental Cup|1996]]\n\n'''Fiorentina'''<ref name=eurosport.com/>\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[2000\u201301 Coppa Italia|2000\u201301]]\n*[[Serie C2]]: 2002\u201303\n\t\n'''Perugia'''<ref name=eurosport.com/>\n*[[Serie C2]]: 1987\u201388\n\n===International===\n'''Italy'''<ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/angelo-di-livio/104077/|title=A. Di Livio|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA European Championship]] (Runner Up): [[UEFA Euro 2000|2000]]\n\n===Orders===\n: [[Image:Cavaliere OMRI BAR.svg|left|50px]] 5th Class / Knight: ''[[Italian orders of merit|Cavaliere Ordine al Merito della Repubblica Italiana]]: 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/Onorificenze.aspx?pag=1558&qIdOnorificenza=&cognome=&nome=&daAnno=1800&aAnno=2015&luogoNascita=&testo=&ordinamento=2 |title=ONORIFICENZE |website=quirinale.it |language=Italian |date=12 July 2000 |accessdate=19 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110070653/http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/Onorificenze.aspx?pag=1558&qIdOnorificenza=&cognome=&nome=&daAnno=1800&aAnno=2015&luogoNascita=&testo=&ordinamento=2 |archivedate=10 January 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Di_Livio_Angelo}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180904011324/http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=1569&squadra=1 FIGC Profile] {{in lang|it}} {{dead link|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Italy Squad 1996 UEFA Euro}}\n{{Italy Squad 1998 World Cup}}\n{{Italy Squad 2000 UEFA Euro}}\n{{Italy Squad 2002 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Livio, Angelo}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rome]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:Reggio Audace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:A.S. Roma players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Perugia Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Calcio Padova players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:ACF Fiorentina players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2000 players]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2008}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Angelo Di Livio\n| image              = KL 2018 (3).jpg\n| caption            = Di Livio in [[Italy national football team|Italy]] colours, 2018\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1966|7|26}}\n| birth_place        = Rome, Italy\n| height             = 1.73 m\n| position           = [[Midfielder]], [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| years1             = 1984\u20131985 |clubs1 = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]                |caps1 = 0   |goals1 = 0\n| years2             = 1985\u20131986 |clubs2 = [[A.C. Reggiana|Reggiana]]      |caps2 = 13  |goals2 = 0\n| years3             = 1986\u20131987 |clubs3 = [[A.G. Nocerina 1910|Nocerina]] |caps3 = 31  |goals3 = 1\n| years4             = 1987\u20131989 |clubs4 = [[A.C. Perugia|Perugia]]        |caps4 = 72  |goals4 = 4\n| years5             = 1989\u20131993 |clubs5 = [[Padova Calcio|Padova]]        |caps5 = 138 |goals5 = 13\n| years6             = 1993\u20131999 |clubs6 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]                    |caps6 = 186 |goals6 = 3\n| years7             = 1999\u20132005 |clubs7 = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]   |caps7 = 169 |goals7 = 8\n| totalcaps          = 609 |totalgoals = 29\n| nationalyears1     = 1995\u20132002 |nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] |nationalcaps1 = 40 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{ITA}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Association football}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Football Championship]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[UEFA Euro 2000|Belgium-Netherlands 2000]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Angelo Di Livio''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8and\u0292elo di \u02c8li\u02d0vjo}}; born 26 July 1966) is a retired [[Association football|football]] [[midfielder]] and [[Defender (association football)|defender]]. He played for several Italian clubs in [[Serie A]] throughout his career, coming to prominence with [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], where he won several domestic and international titles. At international level he also played for the [[Italy national football team|Italian national side]] in two [[FIFA World Cup]]s and two [[UEFA European Football Championship]]s, reaching the final of [[UEFA Euro 2000]].\n\nDuring his playing career he was known as ''soldatino'' (toy soldier) or ''soldatino Di Livio'', a nickname his Juventus teammate at the time [[Roberto Baggio]] gave him because of Di Livio's characteristic way of running up and down the flank.<ref name=\"soldatino\">{{cite news|url=http://www.pianeta-calcio.it/?page=vedi_incontri_vip&id=257|title=Io, \"Soldatino\" Di Livio|date= 23 September 2011 |accessdate= 10 March 2013 |work = Pianeta-Calcio.it }}</ref><ref name=\"cinquantamila\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cinquantamila.it/storyTellerThread.php?threadId=DI+LIVIO+Angelo|title=Biografia di Angelo Di Livio|publisher=www.cinquantamila.it|language=Italian|author1=Maria Elena Ribezzo|author2=Giorgio Dell'Arti|date=17 January 2014|accessdate=29 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in Rome, Di Livio began his career with [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] in 1984. Having failed to make an appearance in his only season for the club, Di Livio played for [[A.C. Reggiana|Reggiana]] (1985\u201386), [[A.G. Nocerina 1910|Nocerina]] (1986\u201387), [[A.C. Perugia|Perugia]] (1987\u201389), [[Padova Calcio|Padova]] (1989\u201393), [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] (1993\u201399) and [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] (1999\u20132005).\n\nHis tireless running and quality crossing made him an important element in the dominant Juventus starting lineup from 1993 to 1999, during one of the most successful periods in the club's history. With Juventus, he won three ''[[Scudetto|scudetti]]'' (Italian A League; [[1994\u201395 Serie A|1995]], [[1996\u201397 Serie A|1997]], [[1997\u201398 Serie A|1998]]) and one [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] title ([[1996 UEFA Champions League Final|1996]]), in addition to two [[Italian Supercup]]s ([[1995 Supercoppa Italiana|1995]], [[1997 Supercoppa Italiana|1997]]), a [[1994\u201395 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], an [[UEFA Supercup]] ([[1996 UEFA Super Cup|1996]]), and an [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]] ([[1996 Intercontinental Cup|1996]]); he also reached the final of the [[1994\u201395 UEFA Cup]].\n\nIn 1999, he moved to Fiorentina, where he [[Captain (association football)|captained]] the team to win the [[2000\u201301 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] during the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301 season]]. In 2002, when AC Fiorentina went bankrupt and was reborn as ''Florentia Viola'' in [[Serie C2]], Di Livio showed his dedication by being the only player to stay with the team, as he played through the depths of Italian football on the climb back to [[Serie A]] in 2004, finally retiring after the conclusion of the [[2004\u201305 Serie A]] season.\n\n==International career==\nDi Livio was capped 40 times for [[Italy national football team|Italy]]. He played for Italy at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]], the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], [[2000 UEFA European Football Championship|Euro 2000]] (where Italy finished in 2nd place), and the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]. His first cap came on 6 September 1995 against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]]; his last on 18 June 2002 against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]]. At Euro 1996, he set-up [[Pierluigi Casiraghi]]'s first goal in the team's 2\u20131 win in the opening group match against [[Russia national football team|Russia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52507/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Instinctive Casiraghi helps Italy sink Russia|publisher=UEFA.com|date=6 October 2003}}</ref> For Italy, he was often used as a holding player to shut down games when the team was ahead, thus sealing the win.\n\n==After retirement==\nAfter retiring, Di Livio worked as a coach in the A.S. Roma Youth System (''Allievi \"Coppa Lazio\"'').<ref>[http://www.asroma.it/GiovaniliList.aspx?Categoria=18 Official AS Roma's site]</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nA quick, experienced, energetic, combative, reliable, and tactically versatile player, Di Livio was usually deployed on the right wing, although he was capable of playing on either flank, as a [[Midfielder#Winger|wide midfielder]], or as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|full-back]] or [[Defender (association football)#Wing-back|wing-back]]; he was also capable of playing in the [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|centre]], as a [[Midfielder#Box-to-box midfielder|box-to-box]] or [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], or even in [[Defender (association football)|defence]]. Although he was not the most naturally talented or skilled footballer, he was a highly consistent player, who was known for his pace, stamina, work-rate, strength, tenacity, mentality, man-marking ability, and [[Cross (football)|crossing]] accuracy, as well as his ability to make attacking runs down the flank, but also track back, which enabled him to cover the wing effectively, and have a successful career.<ref name=\"soldatino\"/><ref name=\"cinquantamila\"/><ref name=\"euro2000\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/italy/squad/774613.stm|title=Euro 2000 Profile: Angelo Di Livio|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"tuttomercatoweb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/rassegna-stampa/di-livio-capello-non-mi-volle-alla-roma-41347|title=Di Livio: \"Capello non mi volle alla Roma\"|publisher=TuttoMercatoWeb.com|language=Italian|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"tuttojuve\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-angelo-di-livio-26504|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Angelo DI LIVIO|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|author=Stefano Bedeschi|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"glance\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/1022803.stm|title=Italy squad at a glance|publisher=BBC|accessdate=7 November 2015|date=14 November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/euro2000/italy/player/delivio.html|title=Profile: Angelo Di Livio|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Phil Cole|date=13 July 2000|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it//1998/luglio/03/Niente_paura_noi_siamo_Italia_ga_0_9807033059.shtml |title=\" Niente paura, noi siamo l' Italia \" |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |author1=Germano Bovolenta |author2=Nicola Cecere |date=3 July 1998 |accessdate=13 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAngelo's son, [[Lorenzo Di Livio|Lorenzo]], is also a footballer;<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.italianfootballdaily.com/serie-keeping-la-famiglia/|title=Serie A- Keeping in it in La Famiglia {{!}} IFD|last=Mason|first=Joshua|date=12 September 2016|work=www.italianfootballdaily.com|publisher=Italian Football Daily|language=en-US|access-date=25 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126005507/http://www.italianfootballdaily.com/serie-keeping-la-famiglia/|archivedate=26 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> a Roma youth product, he currently plays for [[Urbs Sportiva Reggina 1914|Reggina]], on loan from Roma.\n\n==Endorsements==\nAs one of the most popular footballers from his generation, Di Livio has kept his public influence and positive reputation till today. In 2011, Angelo Di Livio was named as \"Brand ambassador\" for [[SKS365]]'s brand planetwin365.<ref name=\"http://sks365.com/planetwin365-renews-cooperation-with-angelo-di-livio/\">planetwin365 renews cooperation with Angelo Di Livio: [http://sks365.com/planetwin365-renews-cooperation-with-angelo-di-livio/ sks365 - planetwin365 renews cooperation with Angelo Di Livio], accessdate: 26 August 2015</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n<ref>{{NFT player|id=10693|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|Cup\n!colspan=2|Continental\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n!colspan=2|Italy\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[Coppa Italia]]\n!colspan=2|[[UEFA|Europe]]\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n|[[A.S. Roma|Roma]]||1984\u201385||[[Serie A]]||0||0||||||||||||\n|-\n|[