ate of Vatican City State]]\n# Cardinal [[Adam Maida|Adam Joseph Maida]] (1990-2009)<ref name=\"CatholicNews\">{{cite web |title=Maida, Adam Joseph |url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/resource.php?n=207 |agency=Catholic News Agency |accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref>\n# [[Allen Henry Vigneron]] (2009\u2013present)<ref name=\"vigneron\">{{cite news |first=Joe |last=Kohn |title=Archbishop Vigneron installed as 10th chief shepherd of Detroit diocese |url=http://www.archdioceseofdetroit.org/mcn/installation.html |work=The Michigan Catholic |date=February 6, 2009 |accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Coadjutor bishop (who did not become diocesan bishop)===\n* [[Peter Paul Lefevere]] (1841\u20131869)\n\n===Auxiliary Bishops===\n*[[Edward D. Kelly|Edward Denis Kelly]] (1910-1919), appointed [[Diocese of Grand Rapids|Bishop of Grand Rapids]]\n*[[Joseph Casimir Plagens]] (1924-1935), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Marquette|Bishop of Sault-Sainte Marie-Marquette]]\n*[[Stephen Stanislaus Woznicki]] (1937-1950), appointed [[Diocese of Saginaw|Bishop of Saginaw]]\n*[[Allen James Babcock]] (1947-1954), appointed [[Diocese of Grand Rapids|Bishop of Grand Rapids]]\n*[[Alexander M. Zaleski|Alexander Mieceslaus Zaleski]] (1950-1964), appointed Coadjutor Bishop and later [[Diocese of Lansing|Bishop of Lansing]]\n*[[John Anthony Donovan]] (1954-1967), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Toledo|Bishop of Toledo]]\n*[[Henry Edmund Donnelly]] (1954-1967)\n*[[Joseph Matthew Breitenbeck]] (1965-1969), appointed [[Diocese of Grand Rapids|Bishop of Grand Rapids]]\n*[[Walter Joseph Schoenherr]] (1968-1995)\n*[[Joseph Leopold Imesch]] (1973-1979), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Joliet in Illinois|Bishop of Joliet in Illinois]]\n*[[Arthur Henry Krawczak]] (1973-1982)\n*[[Dale Joseph Melczek]] (1982-1992), appointed [[Apostolic Administrator]] and later Coadjutor Bishop and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary|Bishop of Gary]]\n*[[Patrick R. Cooney|Patrick Ronald Cooney]] (1982-1989), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Gaylord|Bishop of Gaylord]]\n*[[Moses Anderson|Moses B. Anderson]], SSE (1982-2003)\n* [[Thomas Gumbleton]] (1986-2006)\n*[[Bernard Joseph Harrington]] (1993-1998), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Winona|Bishop of Winona]]\n*[[Kevin Michael Britt]] (1993-2002), appointed Coadjutor Bishop and later [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Grand Rapids|Bishop of Grand Rapids]]\n*[[John Clayton Nienstedt]] (1996-2001), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of New Ulm|Bishop of New Ulm]]\n*[[Leonard Paul Blair]] (1999-2003), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Toledo|Bishop of Toledo]]\n*[[Earl Alfred Boyea, Jr.]] (2002-2008), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lansing|Bishop of Lansing]]\n*[[John Michael Quinn]] (2003-2008), appointed Coadjutor Bishop and later [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Winona|Bishop of Winona]]\n* [[Francis R. Reiss]] (2003-2015)\n* [[Walter A. Hurley]] (2003-2005), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Grand Rapids|Bishop of Grand Rapids]]\n*[[Daniel E. Flores|Daniel Ernest Flores]] (2006-2009), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Brownsville|Bishop of Brownsville]]\n*[[Michael J. Byrnes|Michael Jude Byrnes]] (2011-2016), appointed Coadjutor Archbishop and later [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Agana|Archbishop of Agana in Guam]]\n* [[Donald Hanchon]]<ref name=\"ordination\">{{cite news |title=Three auxililiary bishops of Detroit ordained |first=John T.| last=Greilick |date=May 5, 2011 |work=The Detroit News |url=http://multimedia.detnews.com/pix/photogalleries/newsgallery/20110505BishopsOrdination/index.html |accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref> (2011\u2013present)\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Cepeda|Arturo Cepeda]]<ref name=\"ordination\"/> (2011\u2013present)\n* [[Gerard William Battersby]] (2016\u2013present)\n* [[Robert Joseph Fisher]] (2016\u2013present)\n\n===Other priests of this diocese who became bishops===\n*[[Camillus Paul Maes]], appointed [[Diocese of Covington|Bishop of Covington]] in 1884\n*[[Francis Clement Kelley]], appointed [[Archdiocese of Oklahoma City|Bishop of Oklahoma]] in 1924\n*[[William Murphy (Bishop of Saginaw)|William Francis Murphy]], appointed [[Diocese of Saginaw|Bishop of Saginaw]] in 1938\n*[[Kenneth Edward Untener]], appointed [[Diocese of Saginaw|Bishop of Saginaw]] in 1980\n*[[Alexander Joseph Brunett]], appointed [[Diocese of Helena|Bishop of Helena]] in 1994\n*[[Jeffrey Marc Monforton]], appointed [[Diocese of Steubenville|Bishop of Steubenville]] in 2012\n*[[Robert John McClory]], appointed [[Diocese of Gary|Bishop of Gary]] in 2019\n\n==Schools==\n{{main|List of schools in the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit}}\n[[File:Mercy High School Farmington Hills Michigan.JPG|thumb|[[Mercy High School (Farmington Hills, Michigan)|Mercy High School]] in [[Farmington Hills, Michigan|Farmington Hills]]]]\nAs of 2013 the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit had 96 schools with 30,000 students. As of 2013 there are four Catholic grade schools and three Catholic high schools in the City of Detroit, with all of them in the city's west side.<ref name=Cathschool>{{cite news| url=http://www.freep.com/article/20130201/NEWS01/302010079/Detroit-area-s-Catholic-schools-shrink-but-tradition-endures| title=Detroit area's Catholic schools shrink, but tradition endures| archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6SY5NJ0zC?url=http://www.freep.com/article/20130201/NEWS01/302010079/Detroit-area-s-Catholic-schools-shrink-but-tradition-endures| work=Detroit Free Press| date=February 1, 2013| archivedate=September 13, 2014| first=Patricia| last=Montemurri| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1964-1965 school year, there were 360 schools operated by the archdiocese, with about 110 grade schools in Detroit, Hamtramck, and [[Highland Park, Michigan|Highland Park]] and 55 high schools in those three cities. There were a total of 203,000 students in the Catholic schools. The Catholic school population has decreased due to the increase of [[charter schools]], increasing tuition at Catholic schools, the small number of African-American Catholics, White Catholics moving to suburbs, and the decreased number of teaching nuns.<ref name=Cathschool/>\n\n==Universities and colleges==\n* [[Madonna University]]\n* [[Marygrove College]] (closing in December 2019)<ref>{{cite news| title=Marygrove College to close in December after 92 years in Detroit| url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/marygrove-college-to-close-in-december-after-92-years-in-detroit| date=June 12, 2019| last=Haddad| first=Ken| work=[[WDIV-TV|WDIV News]]}}</ref>\n* [[Sacred Heart Major Seminary]]\n* [[University of Detroit Mercy]]\n\n==Photo gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:FelicianSistersLivoniaChapel.jpg|Chapel (1961) of the [[Felician Sisters]] in Livonia, Michigan - architectural sculpture by [[Corrado Parducci]].\nImage:SouthfieldMiWordofFaithChapelEntrance.jpg|The former ''Duns Scotus College'', once a [[Franciscan]] [[monastery]] in [[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]], is now the non-denominational ''Word of Faith''.\nImage:SouthfieldMiWordofFaithChapelSouth.jpg|Former [[Duns Scotus College]] in Southfield.\nImage:CardinalAdamMaida.jpg|Cardinal Maida outside of the Cathedral of the Most Blessed Sacrament in Detroit\n</gallery>\n\n==Suffragan sees==\n[[File:Ecclesiastical Province of Detroit map 1.png|thumb|Ecclesiastical Province of Detroit]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Gaylord|Diocese of Gaylord]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Grand Rapids|Diocese of Grand Rapids]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kalamazoo|Diocese of Kalamazoo]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lansing|Diocese of Lansing]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Marquette|Diocese of Marquette]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Saginaw|Diocese of Saginaw]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Michigan|Catholicism}}\n* [[Catholic Church by country]]\n* [[Catholic Church hierarchy]]\n* [[Polish Cathedral style]] churches\n* [[Religion in Metro Detroit]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References and further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Godzak |first=Roman |title= Archdiocese of Detroit (Images of America) |year=2000 |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |isbn=978-0-7385-0797-2}}\n* {{cite book |last=Godzak |first=Roman |title=Catholic Churches of Detroit (Images of America) |year=2004 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |isbn= 978-0-7385-3235-6}}\n* {{cite book |last=Godzak |first=Roman |title= Make Straight the Path: A 300 Year Pilgrimage Archdiocese of Detroit |year=2000 |publisher=Editions du Signe |isbn=978-2-7468-0145-5}}\n*{{cite book |author1-link=Eric J. Hill |last1=Hill |first1=Eric J. |first2=John |last2=Gallagher |title=AIA Detroit: The American Institute of Architects Guide to Detroit Architecture |year=2003 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=978-0-8143-3120-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/aiadetroitameric0000hill }}\n* {{cite book |last=Muller |first=Herman Joseph |title=The University of Detroit 1877-1977: A Centennial History |year=1976 |publisher=[[University of Detroit]]|id=ASIN B0006CVJ4S}}\n* {{cite book |last=Tentler |first=Leslie Woodcock |title=Seasons of Grace: A History of the Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit |year=1992 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=978-0-8143-2106-5}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Tutag |first1=Nola Huse |first2=Lucy |last2=Hamilton |title=Discovering Stained Glass in Detroit |publisher=Wayne State University Press |year=1988 |isbn=978-0-8143-1875-1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n*[http://www.aod.org/ Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit Official Site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.aodonline.org/AODOnline Archdiocese of Detroit Website] (Archive)\n*[https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.archdioceseofdetroit.org/ Archdiocese of Detroit Website] (Archive)\n*[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/ddetr.html Archdiocese of Detroit] at http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org\n*[http://www.saadigitalarchive.org/search/Adam%20J.%20Maida \"Letter from Kerala Catholic Association to Rev. Adam J. Maida, Archbishop of Detroit\" in the South Asian American Digital Archive (SAADA)]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Detroit}}\n{{R-C provinces in the United States}}\n{{Religious landmarks in metropolitan Detroit}}\n{{Detroit}}\n{{Metro Detroit}}\n{{Michigan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roman Catholic Archdiocese Of Detroit}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Detroit]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Detroit|*]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit| ]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1833|Detroit]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 19th century|Detroit]]\n[[Category:1833 establishments in Michigan Territory]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Archdiocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Detroit\n| latin             = Archidioecesis Detroitensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language -->\n| image             = Cathedral of the Most Blessed Sacrament (Detroit, Michigan) - exterior.JPG\n| image_size        = 250px\n| image_alt         =\n| caption           = Cathedral of the Most Blessed Sacrament\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = {{flag|United States}}\n| territory         = [[County (United States)|Counties of]] [[Lapeer County, Michigan|Lapeer]], [[Macomb County, Michigan|Macomb]], [[Monroe County, Michigan|Monroe]], [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland]], [[Saint Clair County, Michigan|St. Clair]], and [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne]]\n| province          = Detroit\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} -->\n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 3,901<!-- Area in square kilometers, automatically converted -->\n| population        = 4,260,234\n| population_as_of  = 2017\n| catholics         = 1,159,688<ref name=\"Catholic_